00:00:22.670 --> 00:00:25.810
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: So I'm
just putting In-Q-Tel out

00:00:25.810 --> 00:00:29.530
there as probably the
most extreme example

00:00:29.530 --> 00:00:35.630
of governmental willingness
to intervene in territories

00:00:35.630 --> 00:00:37.690
we thought the government
really wouldn't do.

00:00:37.690 --> 00:00:39.340
Right?

00:00:39.340 --> 00:00:45.870
And, again, it's an example of
this national security state

00:00:45.870 --> 00:00:48.930
doctrine that David
Hart told us about.

00:00:48.930 --> 00:00:53.350
Whatever is needed for national
security, we're going to do,

00:00:53.350 --> 00:00:55.030
however interventionist
it might be.

00:00:55.030 --> 00:00:56.690
And this is a good example.

00:00:56.690 --> 00:01:00.790
So Ruth David, a very
talented former CIA Director

00:01:00.790 --> 00:01:04.720
for Science and
Technology, comes up

00:01:04.720 --> 00:01:12.650
with the idea of creating this
entity to sponsor IT research.

00:01:12.650 --> 00:01:15.540
Because the CIA realized
it was falling behind.

00:01:15.540 --> 00:01:17.810
It wasn't part of
the IT revolution.

00:01:17.810 --> 00:01:20.172
It didn't understand,
wasn't a participant,

00:01:20.172 --> 00:01:22.130
and yet it was going to
be absolutely critical.

00:01:22.130 --> 00:01:25.075
And, of course,
virtually no day passes

00:01:25.075 --> 00:01:26.450
without reading
in the newspapers

00:01:26.450 --> 00:01:30.110
about some latest cyber
security set of issues.

00:01:30.110 --> 00:01:36.440
So In-Q-Tel is set up as a
government venture capital

00:01:36.440 --> 00:01:41.030
firm, a completely unique model.

00:01:41.030 --> 00:01:45.730
And it's aimed at early
stage technology development.

00:01:45.730 --> 00:01:49.780
So the CIA is not new to
technology development.

00:01:49.780 --> 00:01:53.710
I mean, in aerospace, the
U2 and SR-71 blackbird

00:01:53.710 --> 00:01:58.920
are two of the most famous and
spectacular aircraft ever put

00:01:58.920 --> 00:01:59.420
together.

00:01:59.420 --> 00:02:03.560
They were put together
by Lockheed skunk works.

00:02:03.560 --> 00:02:08.840
But In-Q-Tel really is
a very different model.

00:02:08.840 --> 00:02:16.280
So Norm Augustine, who
had been CEO of Lockheed--

00:02:16.280 --> 00:02:20.000
and is the winner of the
president's National Medal

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:22.370
of Technology, by the way,
so a great technologist

00:02:22.370 --> 00:02:25.660
in his own right--

00:02:25.660 --> 00:02:27.660
he helps in the
founding of this.

00:02:27.660 --> 00:02:31.140
And they pick a CEO right
out of Silicon Valley.

00:02:31.140 --> 00:02:35.790
And they've got a board
with ties to IT innovators,

00:02:35.790 --> 00:02:38.850
as well as economic
researchers, and VC firms,

00:02:38.850 --> 00:02:40.570
and tech companies.

00:02:40.570 --> 00:02:47.750
So In-Q-Tel is allowed to
enter into joint ventures, i.e.

00:02:47.750 --> 00:02:51.620
In effect, it can
co-own the companies

00:02:51.620 --> 00:02:55.040
that it's nurturing to
bring along IT technologies

00:02:55.040 --> 00:02:57.650
that the CIA is going
to be interested in.

00:02:57.650 --> 00:03:00.170
It can use sole source grants.

00:03:00.170 --> 00:03:02.240
It can set up open competitions.

00:03:02.240 --> 00:03:05.330
It can award sole source
development contracts.

00:03:05.330 --> 00:03:07.610
It's got a set of powers
here that are really quite

00:03:07.610 --> 00:03:10.700
interventionist in the model.

00:03:10.700 --> 00:03:13.420
And the CIA itself doesn't
review its business deals.

00:03:13.420 --> 00:03:16.340
It's because it's
a bit offshore.

00:03:16.340 --> 00:03:20.930
So it collaborates with the
CIA, but it's independent of it.

00:03:20.930 --> 00:03:23.183
It has this set of
characteristics.

00:03:23.183 --> 00:03:25.100
And we're going to talk
more about these kinds

00:03:25.100 --> 00:03:27.500
of characteristics when
we do the great groups

00:03:27.500 --> 00:03:31.370
class, the seventh class.

00:03:31.370 --> 00:03:34.850
But agile, problem-driven,
solutions-focused,

00:03:34.850 --> 00:03:40.340
team-oriented, technology aware,
output measured, innovative.

00:03:40.340 --> 00:03:44.930
These are all kind
of characteristics

00:03:44.930 --> 00:03:48.260
that In-Q-Tel likes to
say that it's capable of.

00:03:48.260 --> 00:03:50.370
And these are some of
the technology areas

00:03:50.370 --> 00:03:54.560
that In-Q-Tel, in its
earlier stages, worked on.

00:03:54.560 --> 00:03:59.600
So a whole suite of IT-related
and software-related tech

00:03:59.600 --> 00:04:01.200
capabilities.

00:04:01.200 --> 00:04:07.170
So that's the model,
and it's different.

00:04:07.170 --> 00:04:09.930
So, Chris, do you want to
bring us through it quickly.

00:04:12.720 --> 00:04:14.670
CHRIS: So this is a
pretty unique situation.

00:04:14.670 --> 00:04:17.519
Basically, it's kind
of posed as a win-win.

00:04:17.519 --> 00:04:21.390
Like the CIA gets new
tech that they are kind of

00:04:21.390 --> 00:04:23.400
behind in producing.

00:04:23.400 --> 00:04:26.430
And then, these tech
companies, or In-Q-Tel,

00:04:26.430 --> 00:04:28.320
has the opportunity
to get exposure

00:04:28.320 --> 00:04:32.550
to potential big next problems
that they could develop

00:04:32.550 --> 00:04:34.970
commercial products for.

00:04:34.970 --> 00:04:38.460
So one question
that was posed was,

00:04:38.460 --> 00:04:40.530
are there other such
private enterprises

00:04:40.530 --> 00:04:41.980
funded by the government?

00:04:41.980 --> 00:04:44.370
And if not, what is
preventing these partnerships

00:04:44.370 --> 00:04:46.900
from happening.

00:04:46.900 --> 00:04:49.770
I think Bill mentioned that
the Supreme unique case

00:04:49.770 --> 00:04:51.900
so, probably, I
don't think there's

00:04:51.900 --> 00:04:53.610
any other such partnerships.

00:04:53.610 --> 00:04:58.020
But why is that, maybe?

00:04:58.020 --> 00:04:59.730
AUDIENCE: They're
still around, are they?

00:04:59.953 --> 00:05:01.120
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Oh yeah.

00:05:01.120 --> 00:05:04.140
AUDIENCE: They
re-branded as IQT.

00:05:04.140 --> 00:05:05.305
AUDIENCE: Ah, thank you.

00:05:09.960 --> 00:05:15.017
I do remember there was one,
maybe it was similar to DARPA,

00:05:15.017 --> 00:05:17.100
I remember in DARPA, at
least in the next reading,

00:05:17.100 --> 00:05:19.530
there was something
that was similar.

00:05:19.530 --> 00:05:20.470
Oh, that's right.

00:05:20.470 --> 00:05:22.650
So I remember that one of
the points they mentioned

00:05:22.650 --> 00:05:24.150
in this reading,
there was some sort

00:05:24.150 --> 00:05:26.850
of licensing that
corporations needed

00:05:26.850 --> 00:05:28.503
to work with the government.

00:05:28.503 --> 00:05:29.670
Do you remember what it was?

00:05:29.670 --> 00:05:30.503
Like, FRC licensing.

00:05:30.503 --> 00:05:32.587
AUDIENCE: I think we were
just talking about that.

00:05:32.587 --> 00:05:34.920
Like, level of strictness
of the contracts.

00:05:34.920 --> 00:05:37.870
And how In-Q-Tel
works to restructure

00:05:37.870 --> 00:05:41.583
how that contract works so that
they could encourage smaller

00:05:41.583 --> 00:05:43.000
companies that
didn't want to deal

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:46.385
with overwhelming bureaucracy
to join the party.

00:05:46.385 --> 00:05:47.510
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Thanks.

00:05:47.510 --> 00:05:47.930
[INAUDIBLE]

00:05:47.930 --> 00:05:48.430
Good.

00:05:51.250 --> 00:05:55.510
AUDIENCE: I was going to
say, I think agencies similar

00:05:55.510 --> 00:05:58.480
to In-Q-Tel might
be a hard sell,

00:05:58.480 --> 00:06:00.880
because if you think about--

00:06:00.880 --> 00:06:05.080
they probably have a
pretty large employee base,

00:06:05.080 --> 00:06:09.355
and they're privy
to information leak.

00:06:12.070 --> 00:06:14.090
Also, it's going--
kind of directly

00:06:14.090 --> 00:06:19.223
flying in the face of our
aversion to industrial policy.

00:06:19.223 --> 00:06:20.890
So we are picking
winners, in this case.

00:06:20.890 --> 00:06:23.290
So those two things I think
make it really difficult

00:06:23.290 --> 00:06:25.762
to have other agencies
like this ourselves.

00:06:25.762 --> 00:06:27.970
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Right,
because really, in effect,

00:06:27.970 --> 00:06:30.260
In-Q-Tel is a
venture capital firm.

00:06:30.260 --> 00:06:31.882
It's not doing its own research.

00:06:31.882 --> 00:06:33.340
It's a venture
capitalist, and it's

00:06:33.340 --> 00:06:36.940
taking positions in
companies and helping

00:06:36.940 --> 00:06:40.150
drive those companies
towards technology work

00:06:40.150 --> 00:06:45.828
that's going to be relevant to
concerns that the CIA has got.

00:06:45.828 --> 00:06:46.370
Sorry, Chris.

00:06:46.370 --> 00:06:47.540
Go ahead.

00:06:47.540 --> 00:06:48.370
CHLOE: Oh, no, I--

00:06:48.370 --> 00:06:49.620
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Oh, Chloe.

00:06:52.420 --> 00:06:55.600
